ml_tags: (born December 10, 1805, Newburyport, Massachusetts, U.S. died May 24, 1879 Newburyport, Massachusetts, U.S. William Lloyd Garrison “Additionally, in 1833, he played a role in the formation of the American Anti-Slavery Society,”  “he authored its Declaration of Sentiments and took on the role of its inaugural corresponding secretary”. “With reasonable men, I will reason; with humane men I will plead; but to tyrants I will give no  quarter, nor waste arguments where they will certainly be lost.”  William Lloyd Garrison, born on December 10, 1805 in Newburyport, Massachusetts, U.S.. He passed away on May 24, 1879 in New York, He was known as an American  journalistic advocate responsible for the publication of The Liberator (1831–65).  He played a key role in the successful abolitionist movement against slavery in the United States.  . He was wedded to Helen Eliza Benson and gave birth to William Lloyd Garrison Jr, , Fanny Garrison Villard, Wendell Phillips Garrison George Thompson Garrison, and Francis Jackson Garrison.
